TY  - JOUR
AU  - Dannhauser, Caitlin D
AU  - Hoseinzade, Saeid
T1  - The Unintended Consequences of Corporate Bond ETFs: Evidence from the Taper Tantrum
PY  - 2022
Y1  - 2022/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhab031
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 35
IS  - 1
SP  - 51
EP  - 90
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This paper examines whether ETFs are a unique source of corporate bond fragility. Relative to mutual funds, ETFs cater to high-liquidity-demand investors, facilitate positive feedback strategies, and transmit outflows to corporate bonds via near-proportional trading. Comparing yield spread changes of bonds from the same issuer, we show that ETFs create flow-induced pressure during the Taper Tantrum, a period of market turmoil. Redemptions used to maintain the relative price efficiency of the largest and most liquid ETFs lead to significantly higher yield spreads for 4 months before reverting. The pattern indicates ETFs amplify the effects of negative fundamental shocks.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhab031
ER  - 



